<br>
&quot;People tend to be promoted up to their level of incompetence&quot;<br>
<br>
But also remember that a manager is the one ultimately responsible for a project's success.  If it crashes most likely so does he.  His people will tend to stay around even if he's replaced.<br>
<br>
It's probably better to have a manager with few PC skills but great management skills; that's not usually how it works however.  People tend to advance up through a department until they get to a position that they don't do so well in, where they will often stay for years.  That's how you get bad IT managers - old techs/programmers who never could manage real well, but knew their stuff well enough years ago to get promoted.  Since they aren't &quot;hand's on&quot; any longer they don't know the current technology that well either.<br>
<br>
Voila!  Poor management.  It happens many places, but in IT, because of the speed of change and the lack of management and people skills among the average tech population, it tends to be more noticable.<br>
<br>
But heck, what do I know.  I'm an IT manager. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
